Blood supply, new screening test - USA 990310000116
[1
Date: Wed, 10 Mar 1999 13:22:32 -0600
From: Gilpatrick, Sid <sgilpatrick@melnick.mvir.bcm.tmc.edu>

I am curious as to why the NAT is reported to take 48 to 72 hours to
complete. Given today's technology, PCR (even RT-PCR needed for RNA
viruses) can be completed in less than 3 hours. Granted detection of the
PCR product can take up to 12 hours if done by traditional southern
blotting methods but by using a liquid ELISA type detection method this can
be cut to between 3 and 4 hours. This would leave more than 12 hours for
DNA/RNA isolation from the blood and still produce test results within 24
hours of receiving the blood. Am I missing something?.
--
Sidney G. Gilpatrick
Baylor College of Medicine
Dept. of Molecular Virology
(713) 798-4439
e-mail: sg691970@bcm.tmc.edu
