[2
Date: Wed, 10 Mar 1999 10:30:43 -0500
From: Joyce Oliver <JOLIVER@mail.mcg.edu>

I have a concern regarding the implementation of NAT testing (nucleic acid
testing) on blood donors from the United States. While I whole-heartedly
support any testing that narrows the window period between infection and
seroconversion, I disagree with the decision to implement NAT testing with
the intention of releasing the blood products prior to the results being
completed. The Red Cross has declared the implementation a "research
study" and has filed for an Investigational New Drug application with the
FDA to conduct this testing. Hospitals are being "...encouraged to include
a statement that addresses the issue of NAT testing in its transfusion
informed consent process". Although the current estimated rates of
NAT-reactive donations is projected to be low, the possibility certainly
exists of a patient receiving blood products for which he/she will then be
told within a few days that the unit has tested positive for HCV or HIV-1.
If I were a lawyer, I would have a field day with this. If I were a
patient, I would never be able to understand how the hospital had been
allowed to give me a blood product before they had gotten all the test
results back. Platelets only have a 5 day expiration date and perhaps an
exception will have to be made in this case, but I propose that we DO NOT
transfuse any of the other blood components until the NAT results are back
and found to be negative.
--
Joyce Oliver, MT(ASCP)SI
Clinical Immunology Supervisor
Medical College of Georgia
Augusta, GA 30912
e-mail: joliver@mail.mcg.edu
